\begin{abstract}
We show that the cumulative CO emission from galaxies throughout cosmic history distorts the spectrum of the cosmic microwave background (CMB) at a level that is well above the detection limit of future instruments, such as the Primordial Inflation Explorer (PIXIE). The modeled CO signal has a prominent bump in the frequency interval 100-200 GHz, with a characteristic peak intensity of $\sim$ 2$\times$10$^{-23}$ W\,m$^{-2}$\,Hz$^{-1}$\,sr$^{-1}$. Most of the CO foreground originates from modest redshifts, $z \sim$ 2-5, and needs to be efficiently removed for more subtle distortions from the earlier universe to be detected. 
\end{abstract}



